        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2457295837" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4599911894580532332">What an enjoyable book. My biggest complaint is that I kept putting this book into context with the AMC series &quot;Hell on Wheels.&quot; Couldn&apos;t think of Durant without picturing Colm Meaning and wondering when Bohanan would show up ;-)<br/><br/>That being said, the book really did paint a picture of the period. There were sections wherein Ambrose quoted numerous telegrams, letters, or other correspondence to help paint a picture as to what occurred. <br/><br/>Very enjoyable quick book. <br/><br/>The reason why it gets 4 stars and </span>
  <span id="freeText4599911894580532332" style="display:none">What an enjoyable book. My biggest complaint is that I kept putting this book into context with the AMC series "Hell on Wheels." Couldn't think of Durant without picturing Colm Meaning and wondering when Bohanan would show up ;-)<br /><br />That being said, the book really did paint a picture of the period. There were sections wherein Ambrose quoted numerous telegrams, letters, or other correspondence to help paint a picture as to what occurred. <br /><br />Very enjoyable quick book. <br /><br />The reason why it gets 4 stars and not 5 is because it is almost too much of a story. It goes by very quickly without forcing you to think and contemplate what was going on or what was happening. As such, while I enjoyed the book, it is not one that is likely to stay with me over time.</span>
